00:47:04.500 --> 00:47:05.780
BEN FOLDS: That's awesome.

00:47:05.780 --> 00:47:06.710
AUDIENCE: I have two questions.

00:47:06.710 --> 00:47:09.293
If the time is short, maybe you
can choose one or combine them

00:47:09.293 --> 00:47:11.270
into one mega
answer of some sort.

00:47:11.270 --> 00:47:12.950
One question is that you're
one of the few people who's

00:47:12.950 --> 00:47:14.575
been on the radio
for the last 30 years

00:47:14.575 --> 00:47:16.640
and knows lots of
chords and jazz chords

00:47:16.640 --> 00:47:18.866
and knows how to drive
in reverse to a chorus.

00:47:18.866 --> 00:47:20.990
How do you feel that pop
music has sort of left all

00:47:20.990 --> 00:47:22.304
these different chords behind?

00:47:22.304 --> 00:47:22.970
BEN FOLDS: Yeah.

00:47:22.970 --> 00:47:25.880
AUDIENCE: With songs of one
repeating chord progression.

00:47:25.880 --> 00:47:27.620
Number two, quite
different, I always

00:47:27.620 --> 00:47:30.120
admired that when you sang, I
felt like it was actually you,

00:47:30.120 --> 00:47:33.560
like your voice, a part of
you're talking but on notes.

00:47:33.560 --> 00:47:35.900
How did you find
your singing voice?

00:47:35.900 --> 00:47:36.900
BEN FOLDS: Well, thanks.

00:47:36.900 --> 00:47:41.490
I think those are two
really neat points

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:43.460
about music in general.

00:47:43.460 --> 00:47:47.860
The singing thing is
that I didn't think

00:47:47.860 --> 00:47:49.002
I was going to be a singer.

00:47:49.002 --> 00:47:50.960
I thought I would write
songs for other people.

00:47:50.960 --> 00:47:53.230
So the bands that I
played in to begin with,

00:47:53.230 --> 00:47:57.520
I made sure they had singers.

00:47:57.520 --> 00:47:59.620
I always played
in various bands,

00:47:59.620 --> 00:48:01.570
and one or two of
the guys in the band

00:48:01.570 --> 00:48:04.720
would have great voices, and
they would do singery things.

00:48:04.720 --> 00:48:06.310
They sang loudly.

00:48:06.310 --> 00:48:07.330
They used vibrato.

00:48:07.330 --> 00:48:08.950
They did little riffs and stuff.

00:48:08.950 --> 00:48:12.340
And I thought that
would be a good thing.

00:48:12.340 --> 00:48:14.470
I hear the song in my
head, and I think, oh,

00:48:14.470 --> 00:48:17.490
if this has a great singer,
then that'll be a great thing.

00:48:17.490 --> 00:48:20.860
But it wasn't that satisfying
to hear them do that.

00:48:20.860 --> 00:48:22.870
I would make tapes for
them where I would say,

00:48:22.870 --> 00:48:24.520
here's how the song goes.

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:29.260
And the song would
just be humbly speak

00:48:29.260 --> 00:48:31.000
singing would be it.

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:35.200
And I think that the
recordings started

00:48:35.200 --> 00:48:38.332
showing themselves to be a
lot more interesting than what

00:48:38.332 --> 00:48:39.290
we were coming up with.

00:48:39.290 --> 00:48:44.200
And so I would try to get
the singers to not sing,

00:48:44.200 --> 00:48:46.380
to speak on pitches.

00:48:46.380 --> 00:48:51.210
I also had a little
bit of a piano mentor

00:48:51.210 --> 00:48:52.980
for about a year at school.

00:48:52.980 --> 00:48:54.540
I wasn't majoring in piano.

00:48:54.540 --> 00:48:58.960
But for one year before
this guy retired,

00:48:58.960 --> 00:49:03.357
he gave me a full scholarship
to just study piano with him.

00:49:03.357 --> 00:49:05.190
And most of the time,
we didn't study piano.

00:49:05.190 --> 00:49:06.540
We just talked about music.

00:49:06.540 --> 00:49:10.040
And he asked me if I'd
considered how great this guy

00:49:10.040 --> 00:49:10.990
he had just heard.

00:49:10.990 --> 00:49:13.590
He goes, I recently
heard a young man

00:49:13.590 --> 00:49:15.764
by the name of Eric Clapton.

00:49:15.764 --> 00:49:16.680
Have you heard of him?

00:49:16.680 --> 00:49:19.030
Like, yeah, I've
heard of Eric Clapton.

00:49:19.030 --> 00:49:23.460
And he said, he seems to me
to speak on pitches, which

00:49:23.460 --> 00:49:26.490
is interesting, because it
gives more weight to the things

00:49:26.490 --> 00:49:27.960
that he's singing about.

00:49:27.960 --> 00:49:30.930
Why would a man like
that be singing at all

00:49:30.930 --> 00:49:32.552
unless he had something to say?

00:49:32.552 --> 00:49:34.260
And I thought that's
kind of interesting,

00:49:34.260 --> 00:49:36.690
and I think that those things,
I adopted those things.

00:49:36.690 --> 00:49:43.260
As far as chords go, I've
always loved harmony and chords.

00:49:43.260 --> 00:49:49.170
And it can be its
own puzzle, you

00:49:49.170 --> 00:49:53.220
know, the harmony and moving,
even moving key centers,

00:49:53.220 --> 00:49:55.470
and they mean different things.

00:49:55.470 --> 00:50:01.530
And I think that rock
and roll music has,

00:50:01.530 --> 00:50:05.760
sort of like with the voice,
there can be an assumption

00:50:05.760 --> 00:50:11.100
that someone who just plays one
chord must have more to say,

00:50:11.100 --> 00:50:16.582
and that by distracting yourself
with the frivolity of trying

00:50:16.582 --> 00:50:18.540
to drive yourself through
different key centers

00:50:18.540 --> 00:50:22.710
and you're making music
into a Rubik's cube somehow,

00:50:22.710 --> 00:50:27.030
or it's too much ornamentation.

00:50:29.790 --> 00:50:32.190
I think Bob Dylan might have
had a lot to do with that.

00:50:32.190 --> 00:50:35.960
In that, you hear
someone like Dylan,

00:50:35.960 --> 00:50:38.110
the simplicity is
part of what's great.

00:50:38.110 --> 00:50:40.880
He seems like he knows
what he's talking about.

00:50:40.880 --> 00:50:44.290
And he sounds wise,
and almost sounds

00:50:44.290 --> 00:50:46.670
like, I can't be bothered
with all these chords.

00:50:46.670 --> 00:50:47.920
And I've got something to say.

00:50:47.920 --> 00:50:50.480
I don't have time for
this little hobby.

00:50:50.480 --> 00:50:52.480
And so by the time
I came through,

00:50:52.480 --> 00:50:55.240
it was really not cool to
play any more than a couple

00:50:55.240 --> 00:50:57.490
of chords, couple,
three chords, and this

00:50:57.490 --> 00:50:59.450
was during the grunge period.

00:50:59.450 --> 00:51:02.920
And so that's all I
needed to use more chords.

00:51:02.920 --> 00:51:04.070
That kind of pissed me off.

00:51:04.070 --> 00:51:06.340
I felt like, oh,
I'm not allowed?

00:51:06.340 --> 00:51:08.650
All right, punk
rock, let's do this.

00:51:08.650 --> 00:51:12.010
So I would just really
flex that part, because I

00:51:12.010 --> 00:51:13.000
thought it was pretty.

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:15.600
And there's all
sorts of subversion.

00:51:15.600 --> 00:51:23.680
And in the punk rock culture,
playing piano in itself

00:51:23.680 --> 00:51:26.080
was offensive.

00:51:26.080 --> 00:51:27.270
So we would play.

00:51:27.270 --> 00:51:28.300
That's what we booked.

00:51:28.300 --> 00:51:32.470
We just booked punk rock grunge
clubs during most of the '90s.

00:51:32.470 --> 00:51:38.830
And I loved looking out and
playing jazz chords and like--

00:51:38.830 --> 00:51:39.400
That's nice.

00:51:39.400 --> 00:51:41.380
I enjoyed that.

00:51:41.380 --> 00:51:42.130
ALAN SEALES: Cool.

00:51:42.130 --> 00:51:42.796
All right, yeah?

00:51:42.796 --> 00:51:44.110
Final quick question.

00:51:44.110 --> 00:51:45.560
Then we get to
some performances.

00:51:45.560 --> 00:51:47.290
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:51:47.290 --> 00:51:50.530
So I was always interested
in how just creative a lot

00:51:50.530 --> 00:51:51.520
of your music is.

00:51:51.520 --> 00:51:53.290
And I'm a hobbyist composer.

00:51:53.290 --> 00:51:56.050
And sometimes, I get stuck
into doing similar song

00:51:56.050 --> 00:51:58.270
structures or similar chords.

00:51:58.270 --> 00:52:01.330
So I was wondering if you
had any tips that maybe you

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:04.960
used to try and get yourself
to be more creative?

00:52:04.960 --> 00:52:09.460
BEN FOLDS: Well, I don't think
that using the same structure

00:52:09.460 --> 00:52:15.670
over and over again
necessarily has to do anything

00:52:15.670 --> 00:52:16.930
with the creative part.

00:52:16.930 --> 00:52:19.420
I think you can be really,
really creative within a really

00:52:19.420 --> 00:52:21.010
confined sort of structure.

00:52:21.010 --> 00:52:25.750
You could decide that you
were the guy who was AB guy,

00:52:25.750 --> 00:52:28.120
and you were going to write
it all in the same key,

00:52:28.120 --> 00:52:30.850
and that would be fine.

00:52:30.850 --> 00:52:36.480
If you feel like that's
limiting you in some way,

00:52:36.480 --> 00:52:39.720
then I don't know.

00:52:39.720 --> 00:52:42.420
I think it's
important to remember

00:52:42.420 --> 00:52:45.420
that a song is there
to communicate a thing,

00:52:45.420 --> 00:52:51.160
and that it needn't
do anymore than that.

00:52:51.160 --> 00:52:54.930
I think that can free you
up a lot in form and key

00:52:54.930 --> 00:52:58.290
and everything, because the
necessity to communicate

00:52:58.290 --> 00:53:02.160
the thing that you're coming
up with means that that drives.

00:53:02.160 --> 00:53:04.020
That drives things.

00:53:04.020 --> 00:53:07.620
You might have a cadence
where you thought you were

00:53:07.620 --> 00:53:10.320
going to end on I don't know.

00:53:10.320 --> 00:53:11.850
If you had gone--

00:53:11.850 --> 00:53:14.334
[PIANO MUSIC]

00:53:14.334 --> 00:53:15.500
And that was really similar.

00:53:15.500 --> 00:53:16.870
It's just like that's all it is.

00:53:16.870 --> 00:53:23.462
And then you get stuck in
something way too long.

00:53:23.462 --> 00:53:25.170
There's something
complicated about that.

00:53:25.170 --> 00:53:27.670
But the fact that you got stuck
in it so long says something

00:53:27.670 --> 00:53:30.800
about how you were stuck in your
life, or your ideas, or the way

00:53:30.800 --> 00:53:33.490
you felt about it, or that
you were scared to progress

00:53:33.490 --> 00:53:35.660
in your life, or you were
scared of what's next,

00:53:35.660 --> 00:53:39.400
or you just you were
high and you couldn't

00:53:39.400 --> 00:53:40.400
remember the next chord.

00:53:40.400 --> 00:53:42.290
Who knows what it might be.

00:53:42.290 --> 00:53:45.530
But if always your--

00:53:45.530 --> 00:53:48.840
that was really nothing.

00:53:48.840 --> 00:53:51.770
I shouldn't even
have played that.

00:53:51.770 --> 00:53:57.050
I think that's the first thing
is always, how do you feel?

00:53:57.050 --> 00:53:58.900
How does this moment feel?

00:53:58.900 --> 00:54:01.690
How can you get that across?

00:54:01.690 --> 00:54:06.080
Then if you need more
vocabulary, you'll find it.

00:54:06.080 --> 00:54:08.710
If you can't find the
word, it doesn't come out,

00:54:08.710 --> 00:54:11.630
then that's when you
reach for the thesaurus.

00:54:11.630 --> 00:54:12.190
You know?

00:54:12.190 --> 00:54:13.430
You think about those things.

00:54:13.430 --> 00:54:16.550
And I think the same is
true of song structure.

00:54:16.550 --> 00:54:21.450
I always like to play
with song structure.

00:54:21.450 --> 00:54:25.940
I like to question it too much.

00:54:25.940 --> 00:54:29.170
So while I'm writing, it's
always a concern of mine

00:54:29.170 --> 00:54:32.470
that it doesn't have
the same structure.

00:54:32.470 --> 00:54:36.760
And a lot of times I find that
the effect that the song was

00:54:36.760 --> 00:54:40.540
having on me emotionally
before I messed with it so much

00:54:40.540 --> 00:54:41.062
was there.

00:54:41.062 --> 00:54:42.520
And then I messed
with it and tried

00:54:42.520 --> 00:54:44.300
to do something odd with it.

00:54:44.300 --> 00:54:46.180
So what I do then
because I'm not

00:54:46.180 --> 00:54:48.730
getting the chill at that point,
or I'm not hearing applause

00:54:48.730 --> 00:54:51.070
in the back of my head
at the end of the song,

00:54:51.070 --> 00:54:53.290
it's not doing the
thing, I go back

00:54:53.290 --> 00:54:56.240
and I put it into a really
predictable song structure.

00:54:56.240 --> 00:55:01.600
And I mean down to the point
where I'm timing the intro.

00:55:01.600 --> 00:55:04.540
Because if the intro is not
falling between 12 and 15

00:55:04.540 --> 00:55:08.662
seconds, then maybe I
should lay out the songs

00:55:08.662 --> 00:55:10.120
so that it falls
at the right time.

00:55:10.120 --> 00:55:14.240
For some reason, we want to
hear a chorus at one minute.

00:55:14.240 --> 00:55:15.120
I don't know why.

00:55:15.120 --> 00:55:16.240
But sometimes,
you want to hear--

00:55:16.240 --> 00:55:18.656
so there are certain songs
that work so well, because they

00:55:18.656 --> 00:55:21.120
start with the chorus.

00:55:21.120 --> 00:55:24.870
And like I don't know, something
like "Dancing Queen" by Abba,

00:55:24.870 --> 00:55:30.360
which that's a fun song, because
it starts with the bridge.

00:55:30.360 --> 00:55:32.540
You can dance.

00:55:32.540 --> 00:55:35.850
It's like the party
was just going.

00:55:35.850 --> 00:55:39.210
And then the doors
open, and you're in it.

00:55:39.210 --> 00:55:41.850
And there's something really
compelling about that.

00:55:41.850 --> 00:55:43.650
That's when you mess with form.

00:55:43.650 --> 00:55:46.260
Otherwise, I think the
form can be your friend.

00:55:46.260 --> 00:55:49.500
That's as much as I-- that's
my whole upload on form there.

00:55:49.500 --> 00:55:50.950
ALAN SEALES: That's great.

